UGHELLI – The Delta State Commissioner for Water Resources Development, Rt. Hon. Evelyn Omavowan Oboro Esq., has commiserated with Mrs. Rose Ezewu, Commissioner for Secondary Education on the death of her mother, Madam Agnes Kioja Alerubor. Oboro in a statement by her Senior Special Assistant on Media and Publicity, Hon. Sunday Apah, described the late Madam Agnes Kioja Alerubor as “a mother with rare and impeccable qualities,” adding that the people of Okwegume community would miss her greatly, especially for her support towards the upliftment of the community and Okpe Kingdom in general. Despite Security Challenges, Nigeria Is Not A Failed Nation –… SMEs: Ugwuanyi Empowers Enugu Youths Through Cyber Security… She said in the statement that Mama was a different mother, deep in knowledge, uncompromisingly disciplined and always pushing her children to be societal examples of humanity and excellence. Oboro also noted that Mama has left a big vacuum in her family, just as she stated that it was indeed a tough time for Mrs. Ezewu and her siblings who enjoyed a great motherly chemistry with their late mother. She prayed that God should give the family the fortitude to bear the irreparable loss. “We share in your grief as you mourn the loss of your beloved mother, especially at this time when her wise counsel would have been of immense benefit to you as a serving commissioner in the state”, she added.